      body: "Lambda cold start occurs when AWS must initialise a new execution environment for a Lambda function that has not been invoked recently downloading the deployment package, starting the runtime, and executing the initialisation code outside the handler. Cold starts add 100ms-2s of additional latency on the first invocation after an idle period. For Node.js Lambda functions with small packages: cold starts are typically 100-300ms acceptable for non-latency-sensitive APIs and background processing. For Node.js with large packages, or Python/Java runtimes: cold starts can be 500ms-2s potentially unacceptable for user-facing APIs. Mitigations: Provisioned Concurrency (pre-warm a number of Lambda instances guaranteed sub-millisecond start), code optimisation (reduce package size, defer heavy initialisation), SnapStart (Java snapshot initialised environment, 90% cold start reduction), and Graviton2/ARM64 (20% cheaper, 19% better price-performance). For user-facing APIs where cold start is a concern, ECS Fargate (no cold start) is often the correct choice over Lambda.",
